<br>
Love KEI.  Glad that people sit and sell it all day long. <br>
Glad that getting my new caster from 1 to 50 didn't require me grouping with anyone at all because I really didn't want to bother.  Melee char, you drop a bunch of AC/HP gear and some low delay weaps...  caster you get KEI.  It's almost balanced now for PLing new characters. <br>
<br>
People who don't feel like lowbies should be able to receive KEI(at a point when EQ is 4 years old and most of the playerbase accounts have at least one character over level 50 anyway) have some issues.  <br>
<br>
On Luclin, there's typically one or two KEI folks in the nexus always. <br>
Payment there is donation.  Never seen anyone attach a specific price per cast.  My typical donation is 15 - 25p depending on my mood. <br>
Lots of the KEI people offer to cast for free.  Some always give KEI to clerics free.  <br>
<br>
It's interesting that the enchanters have this unique niche in the game.  They have the ideal situation for pursuing tradeskills to earn a lot of cash and also this alternative way of making pp just sitting around casting a spell over and over. <br>
<br>
Ironically, what purpose does the big pile of cash serve? <br>
My guesses are: <br>
The secondary market (selling the pp for RL cash)<br>
Twinking other characters (ooh boy, more twinks!)<br>
Buying the enchanter who is making the pp more gear... (which is, in all likelihood, inferior to what he/she could acquire if they were out raiding instead of casting KEI)<br>
<br>
Economically speaking: <br>
KEI is a high demand &quot;product&quot; since is it long lasting, and centrally distributed.<br>
If you could, somehow, get every enchanter to join KPEC (KEI Producing Enchanter Collective), you could regulate prices and put a stranglehold on the whole EQ world.  But since that is unlikely to happen (due to free will, differing agendas, number of enchanters involved) the deregulated KEI market is certain to continue.<br>
As the EQ demographics move towards the higher levels and more KEI spells enter the game (never to be removed due to the highly realistic economic model), supply keeps increasing and demand decreases.  Soon, it will be more common to have multiple KEI vendors in the nexus simultaneously competeing for the business.  Some crazy people might even give it away at every opportunity.  Like so many other things in EQ, the window of making the most possible cash from something is limited.  So, if you weren't one of the first enchanters selling KEI, you may not have missed your opportunity to make money, but if your plan is to KEI your way to 1,000,000pp at this point, you're odds aren't so hot. <br>
<br>
Look on the bright side...  EQ population base is due for a steep decline in the coming months maybe you could be the last enchanter left selling KEI after the exodus.  Or alternatively, I hear there's an emerging &quot;Rune&quot; market <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Zommi<br>
Luclin<br>
<br>
